Dear Dr. Sierra,

I am writing to you directly with a brief inquiry about the Impetus Grants program, where Hevolution served as a co-funder in Rounds 2 and 3.

I am PI of a longevity research program at the Georgia Longevity Alliance (Abastumani, Georgia) and a PhD candidate at UNED Madrid (starting Autumn 2026). My project tests the Centriolar Damage Accumulation Theory of Aging (CDATA) — Counter #1 in the Multi-Counter Architecture of Organismal Aging (MCAOA).

Project in brief:
- Phase A (6 months, EUR 78,594): Two autonomous AI-driven fluorescence microscopes (ARGUS-LP) for single-cell centriole lineage tracking in human fibroblasts.
- Phase B (12 months, EUR 100,000): In vivo competitive bone marrow transplant assay (~150 mice, 4 arms) at Universitaet Ulm (Prof. Hartmut Geiger, co-PI — letter signed).
- Co-PI: Elizabeth Parrish (BioViva — letter signed).
- Open science: OSF pre-registration (DOI 10.17605/OSF.IO/KQBY4), GitHub, Zenodo.
- PI track record: 10 PubMed-indexed publications on centriolar biology and aging, Rust/Cell-DT simulation (439 tests).

I have tried reaching Norn Group (info@norn.group, team@norn.group) but have not received a reply, and Hevolution's info@hevolution.org is non-functional (DNS SERVFAIL). I am resending to info@hevolution.com and copying you in hopes that you can clarify:

1. Is Impetus Grants continuing under Norn Group?
2. Is there a Round 4 planned?
3. Are there other Hevolution programs suitable for a ~EUR 180k high-risk mechanistic aging experiment?

I would be deeply grateful for any guidance or a brief pointer to the right contact. I have a complete submission packet ready.

Thank you for your time and for your many years of leadership in aging research.

